RISK PREDICTION OF DOMESTIC BATTERY FOR CHICAGO

Hanyong Xu

11/07/2019

In this analysis, the risk of domestic batteries in the city of Chicago is predicted using a machine learning model. Such a model could potentially increase the policing efficiency by directing officers where to focus for the patrols, but it might also suffer from the selection bias originated from different demographics. The accuracy and generalizability will be evaluated and a recommendation of whether the proposed model should be put into production will be delivered in the end.

Domestic battery in 2018 is chosen as the outcome variable. It is downloaded from the Chicago Open Data website. Its distribution is mapped below. The selection bias for this crime is mostly from reporting bias. This variable is prone to selection bias for three reasons: 1) people experiencing domestic violence are often afraid of reporting the violence, they may be afraid of worsening the family relationship or reputation; 2) victims are sometimes not aware of their rights to report, or have no means of reporting, especially for children; 3) domestic violence is hard to be reported by people from the outside since it happens inside a household. The bias is likely linked to race and education levels, which will be discussed in the later sections of this markdown.

dbatt <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Crimes-2018/3i3m-jwuy") %>% 
  filter(Primary.Type == "BATTERY" &

         Y = as.numeric(Y)) %>% 
  na.omit %>%

2.2 Risk Factors / Predictors

The risk factors data are downloaded from the Chicago Open Data as well. Risk factors used include: abandoned cars, abandoned buildings, graffiti, street lights out, sanitation problems, liquor retailors, family support centers, connect centers for jobs, and health clinics. Family support centers and connect centers might support families, foster social interactions, and create opportunities for public supervision. The health clinics provide the people the access to both mental and physical health treatment. These predictors are joined to the fishnet and plotted below.

Other predictors include the neighborhood, the police beats and districts, and the distance to The Loop.

3. Feature Engineering

3.1 Nearest Neighbor Features

To better capture the spatial quality of the predictors, the distance of each crime data point to the closest of each amenity/risk is calculated. For certain factors, three or five closest neighboring amenities/risks are chosen for the calculation because of their high density. These new features are then joined with the fishnet and plotted below.

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
    output <-
      as.data.frame(nn) %>%
      rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
      gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
      group_by(thisPoint) %>%
      summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
      dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
      pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

3.4 Exploring the Spatial Structure of Battery

Local Moran’s I is calculated to find the existing spatial autocorrelation of the domestic batty crimes. A hotspot is also mapped below showing the highly significant risky regions.

final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(
    as.data.frame(localmoran(final_net$countBatt, final_net.weights)),
    as.data.frame(final_net, NULL)) %>% 
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(Battery_Count = countBatt, 
                  Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                  P_Value = `Pr(z > 0)`) %>%
    mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.05, 1, 0)) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)
  
vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="", option = "B") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme()}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Morans I statistics, Domestic Battery"))

final_net <-
  final_net %>% 
  mutate(batt.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(final_net$countBatt, 
                                            final_net.weights)[,5] <= 0.0000001, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(batt.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),

                                             filter(final_net, batt.isSig == 1))), 1 ))

4. Regression and Validation

4.1 Poisson Regression

Poisson regression is chosen as the model to use here because crime is happening in low probability in general, thus, using a binomial logit model might leads to unreasonable thresholds selection.

ggplot(final_net, aes(countBatt)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Domestic Battery by Grid Cell")

4.2 Cross-validated Poisson Regression

There are two cross-validations conducted. The first type seperate the dataset into 100 folds, and each fold is tested when the rest of the data are trained. The second type use the neighborhood to do the cross validation: each neighborhood of data is tested when the rest of the data are trained.

There are two sets of input data. The first set does not include spatial structures while the seconde set does. Only one features from each variable is selected to avoid multicollinearity. The Family Support Center predictor is dropped since it has little correlation and results in higher MAE.

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn5", "Abandoned_Cars.nn3", "Graffiti.nn3", 
              "Liquor_Retail.nn1", "Street_Lights_Out.nn5", "Sanitation.nn3", "loopDistance",
              "healthClinic.nn1", "ConnectCenter.nn3")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn5", "Abandoned_Cars.nn3", "Graffiti.nn3", 
                 "Liquor_Retail.nn1", "Street_Lights_Out.nn5", "Sanitation.nn3", "loopDistance",
                 "healthClinic.nn1", "ConnectCenter.nn3",  
                 "batt.isSig", "batt.isSig.dist")
crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {

allPredictions <- data.frame()
cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])

for (i in cvID_list) {

  thisFold <- i
  cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")

  fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  
  regression <-
    glm(countBatt ~ ., family = "poisson", 
      data = fold.train %>% 
      dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
  
  thisPrediction <- 
    mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
  allPredictions <-
    rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}

5.2 Predicted Errors

From both the maps and the table below, one can tell that the models with the spatial structure perform better with lower errors. The error is greater for leave-one-group-out cross validation (LOGO cv) than that of the k-fold cross validation. The LOGO cv reflects the model’s ability to generalize across neighborhoods.

The MAE is around 3.9, which means on average the prediction deviates from the true counts by 3.9 counts of domestic batteries. For context, the mean of the countBatt is 8.969155.

6. Conclusion

Even though the model is more accurate in predicting the high-risk regions than the current method of kernel density used by the Chicago Police, the model is unable to generalize across different racial and education groups, which might exasperate the selection bias and results in further over-policing. The above maps and barplot comparing the kernel density and the risk prediction results demonstrate that in general, our model is able to identify latent risks in the high-risk regions. This is useful to help the police force to identify potential risks and direct them for more efficient policing. However, the model also underpredicts the mid-risk regions, which might lead to insufficient policing in these regions.

On the other hand, the generalizability section above demonstrates that our model is incapable of predicting with the same accuracy across different racial and education groups. It over-predicts the non-White or the low-education neighborhoods with high risks and under predicts the White or the high-education neighborhoods. This is potentially problematic since the over-prediction might lead to over-policing, while the other regions will be lack of police force. Furthermore, the over-predicted regions were predicted with high risks because of the existing selection bias of the data set, and our model will only make neighborhoods being overpoliced be overpoliced more. It is unfair and unethical to do so. Thus, the model should not be put into production until the generalizability of the model across different groups is improved.
